    Animal[] objAnimal = {new Cat()};

is a shortcut for

    Animal[] objAnimal = new Animal[] {new Cat()};

which is a shortcut for

    Animal[] objAnimal = new Animal[1];
    objAnimal[0] = new Cat();

The compiled code is identical. So looking at the last variant, it should become obvious that you can do

    Cat objCat0 = (Cat)objAnimal[0];

because you previously stored a reference to a `Cat` instance, created via `new Cat()`, to `objAnimal[0]` whereas

    Cat[] objCatArray = (Cat[]) objAnimal;

is invalid because `objAnimal` contains a reference to an `Animal[]` array instance, created via `new Animal[1]`. The fact that there’s a `Cat` reference stored in one element doesn’t change the type of the array. There could be a subsequent `objAnimal[0] = new Animal();` at any time.

The array initializer syntax used in your question exists for convenience, but doesn’t change the logic. So

    Animal[] objAnimal = {new Cat()};
    objAnimal[0] = new Animal();

is valid and

    Cat[] objCatArray = (Cat[]) objAnimal;

must fail as otherwise you could subsequently use

    Cat cat = objCatArray[0];

without a cast, despite the possibility of the `objAnimal[0] = new Animal()` assignment.

